WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.200
My name is Jim. I'm a software engineer at RStudio. Today I wanted to have a dialog about

00:00:14.200 --> 00:00:22.840
dependencies. So first some ground rules. So all R code has dependencies. Even if your

00:00:22.840 --> 00:00:32.599
R code is just, so those are like treats. So that dog is very well trained. All R code

00:00:32.599 --> 00:00:36.160
has dependencies. Even if your code is just an R script and it depends on nothing but

00:00:36.160 --> 00:00:41.740
base R, base R itself depends on system libraries and those depend on the compiler tool chain

00:00:41.740 --> 00:00:46.160
that was used and ultimately the machine that the code is running on. So really you cannot

00:00:46.160 --> 00:00:53.599
get away from dependencies. And the flip side of that is dependencies inevitably break.

00:00:53.599 --> 00:00:59.599
So this cat is being, you know, like cats are sometimes and destroying the tower. So

00:00:59.599 --> 00:01:06.160
some examples of this in the JavaScript community are the left pad package was removed by the

00:01:06.160 --> 00:01:12.639
maintainer from the repository and destroyed a bunch of websites, like millions of websites.

00:01:13.480 --> 00:01:20.400
Another example is the event stream package had a malicious maintainer that added credential

00:01:20.400 --> 00:01:30.040
harvesting code to the package. And those are like actively malicious actors, maintainers,

00:01:30.040 --> 00:01:37.400
but the more common phenomenon is bit rot where you have your code works fine, some

00:01:37.400 --> 00:01:43.480
time passes, the dependencies change and now your code no longer works.

00:01:43.480 --> 00:01:51.300
So in addition to this, there's often this case, so this is an XKCD of Python, the various

00:01:51.300 --> 00:01:58.120
methods that you can install packages in Python. And when people run into these installation

00:01:58.120 --> 00:02:06.919
problems and dependency problems, they, this is colloquially termed dependency hell. And

00:02:06.919 --> 00:02:15.039
often people, when they encounter this, there's a sort of a movement to a less is more approach

00:02:15.039 --> 00:02:21.160
for dependencies. And while I think this philosophy is really nice for architecture, I don't really

00:02:21.160 --> 00:02:26.600
feel like this is a great solution to the problem in software.

00:02:26.600 --> 00:02:34.600
And why is this? Primarily because I don't think you can treat all dependencies as equivalent.

00:02:34.600 --> 00:02:38.360
And sort of to illustrate this point, let's go through some dependencies. So this is looking

00:02:38.360 --> 00:02:44.960
at the CRAN landing pages, just that CRAN provides. And this package is the Rlang package.

00:02:44.960 --> 00:02:51.399
We can see it depends only on R itself. It doesn't depend on any additional packages.

00:02:51.399 --> 00:02:57.080
In contrast to that, this is the CNV scope package. And this package now depends on over

00:02:57.080 --> 00:03:01.800
40 other packages, which themselves depend on additional packages. And this is depending

00:03:01.800 --> 00:03:08.559
on packages not just on CRAN but also on bioconductor. So clearly we shouldn't be treating

00:03:08.559 --> 00:03:17.240
these two packages as equivalent in this respect. As another aspect of how packages differ,

00:03:17.240 --> 00:03:24.800
this is the, so CRAN provides on their landing page the check results for all packages. And

00:03:24.800 --> 00:03:34.279
in those check results, the column I'm highlighting is the median time to install those packages

00:03:34.279 --> 00:03:39.199
on CRAN's build machines. So this is the glue package I maintain. And you can see the time

00:03:39.199 --> 00:03:45.759
to install is very short for this package. And this is the read R package that I also

00:03:45.759 --> 00:03:52.000
maintain. And you can see these installation times are much, much higher. So the glue installation

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:59.320
times were only 5 to 10 seconds. I guess Windows is slow, so it was 24. But the read

00:03:59.320 --> 00:04:05.839
R package is much, much higher. So these are well over 200, all the way up to 700 seconds.

00:04:05.839 --> 00:04:12.679
So clearly we cannot treat glue and read R the same in terms of this aspect.

00:04:12.679 --> 00:04:19.079
Another aspect that's useful is the binary size of the package. So typically when users

00:04:19.079 --> 00:04:23.760
are installing packages, they're installing binaries from CRAN. And there's a wide range

00:04:23.760 --> 00:04:29.519
of the size of those binaries. So the AWS package is the smallest package on CRAN. It

00:04:29.519 --> 00:04:36.640
has, its size is less than 10 kilobytes. In contrast, the H2O package is over 100 megabytes

00:04:36.640 --> 00:04:43.959
in size. And if you go and look at the bioconductor repositories, the largest binary package on

00:04:43.959 --> 00:04:50.399
bioconductor is over 4 gigabytes in size. So clearly we cannot treat a 4 gigabyte package

00:04:50.399 --> 00:04:58.279
and a 10 kilobyte package as the same. Another aspect is how hard it is to install

00:04:58.279 --> 00:05:05.679
the system requirements for a package. So often, so most packages only depend on R itself

00:05:05.679 --> 00:05:11.440
to install. They don't have any compiled code. So they only need R. You don't even need an

00:05:11.440 --> 00:05:18.640
additional compiler or tool chain. In contrast, so this is the RGDAL package. And it has extensive

00:05:18.640 --> 00:05:24.239
system requirements that are very hard to configure. So this whole paragraph at the

00:05:24.239 --> 00:05:28.600
bottom is the instructions on what you need to do to install and configure the system

00:05:28.600 --> 00:05:33.839
dependencies for this package. Another good example is our friend R Java.

00:05:33.839 --> 00:05:40.519
So there's not one, not two, but three stack overflow posts, all with about 100 upvotes

00:05:40.519 --> 00:05:47.920
of people having problems installing or running R Java on Windows, Mac OS, and Linux. So clearly

00:05:47.920 --> 00:05:55.079
this is a package that is not as easy to install and use as some other packages.

00:05:55.079 --> 00:05:59.200
So all this is to show you that we should not be treating dependencies as equivalent.

00:05:59.200 --> 00:06:04.440
You cannot say a package has 10 dependencies and it's clearly the same as a different package

00:06:04.440 --> 00:06:10.799
that also has 10 dependencies. We need to treat these things differently.

00:06:10.799 --> 00:06:17.799
So what should we do instead? So I think really when you're deciding whether or not to have

00:06:17.799 --> 00:06:22.920
a dependency in your package or to use a certain package because it has so many dependencies,

00:06:22.920 --> 00:06:33.440
you need to weigh some things. And this, how this scale works really depends on your personal

00:06:33.440 --> 00:06:41.320
use case and the users of your code. So if you're, so if you have more dependencies,

00:06:41.320 --> 00:06:49.079
you gain more features, more bug fixes, more testing of those features because other users

00:06:49.079 --> 00:06:57.000
are using your dependencies, but you, but if you don't, if you have fewer dependencies,

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:03.359
you instead have less installation time, less, you use less disk space, you potentially

00:07:03.359 --> 00:07:10.640
have less breakage in your code because you don't depend on an external package. So having

00:07:10.640 --> 00:07:16.179
more dependencies gives you more developer time, so it takes you less, you as the developer

00:07:16.179 --> 00:07:23.239
less time, but you lose generality. So really I think you need to consider your

00:07:23.239 --> 00:07:29.720
users as like the, as when you're making these decisions. If the package you're writing

00:07:29.720 --> 00:07:33.720
or the project you're using is really meant for other package developers to include your

00:07:33.720 --> 00:07:43.000
package in theirs, the installation time becomes more of a factor. So it's more costly if other

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:50.320
packages are trying to depend on your package. And in addition, smaller, more focused packages

00:07:50.320 --> 00:07:57.119
are easier to include and depend on than larger, broader packages. And in this context,

00:07:57.119 --> 00:08:02.880
I think stability is often more important than features. It's more important if the

00:08:02.880 --> 00:08:09.399
package is stable over time than if it continually gains new additional features. In contrast,

00:08:09.399 --> 00:08:16.880
if your users are primarily other data scientists or statisticians that are loading your package

00:08:16.880 --> 00:08:21.839
in R scripts, the installation time in that case is very cheap. So those people are probably

00:08:21.839 --> 00:08:27.320
going to install your package once or just a handful of times. And often if you're depending

00:08:27.320 --> 00:08:32.840
on other packages that are widely, that are highly used in the community, those packages

00:08:32.840 --> 00:08:38.479
often are already installed already. So the users don't even have to install those for

00:08:38.479 --> 00:08:43.880
the most time, for the most part. And in this case, in this context, really the features

00:08:43.880 --> 00:08:48.760
are the most important thing you need to worry about. So if your code is really meant

00:08:48.760 --> 00:08:56.799
more in this context, you're more likely to include additional dependencies.

00:08:56.799 --> 00:09:00.960
In addition, once you sort of decide that you want to replace a given dependency, it's

00:09:00.960 --> 00:09:08.000
important to take into account this phenomenon of illusionary superiority. So people just

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:13.799
as a whole, and I include myself in this, have a very hard time rating themselves against

00:09:13.799 --> 00:09:19.400
the rest of the population. So some examples are like in teaching ability, there was a

00:09:19.400 --> 00:09:25.280
survey done in the University of Nebraska Lincoln faculty, and they were supposed to

00:09:25.280 --> 00:09:31.679
rate their teaching ability versus the rest of the faculty. And in this survey, 68% of

00:09:31.679 --> 00:09:39.080
them responded that they were in the top 25% of the faculty. So in another example,

00:09:39.080 --> 00:09:46.080
in driving skill, so 93% of U.S. respondents to the survey, and 69% of Swedish respondents

00:09:46.080 --> 00:09:52.880
put them in the top 50% of drivers. So clearly a lot of people are vastly overrating their

00:09:52.880 --> 00:10:01.200
own abilities. So how this relates to this issue is don't, just because you think you

00:10:01.200 --> 00:10:09.719
might be good at programming and that the problem maybe doesn't seem that hard, you're

00:10:09.719 --> 00:10:15.799
very likely to overrate the difficulty of the problem and sort of your own ability to

00:10:15.799 --> 00:10:22.599
reproduce the results of the dependency you're trying to replace. So really avoid, so some

00:10:22.599 --> 00:10:28.440
pitfalls of removing dependencies, avoid this overestimation of abilities, and people often

00:10:28.440 --> 00:10:33.640
underestimate how easy it is to introduce new bugs. I guess I've been programming long

00:10:33.640 --> 00:10:37.679
enough that I just assume I will be introducing new bugs when I'm rewriting code. It's just

00:10:37.679 --> 00:10:43.479
like you do your best to try to avoid it, but it just seems like it's inevitable, it

00:10:43.479 --> 00:10:51.640
always happens. In addition, a benefit of using widely used packages is not that necessarily

00:10:51.640 --> 00:10:56.440
those authors of those packages are better or worse at programming than you might be,

00:10:56.440 --> 00:11:01.239
but because they're widely used, they have a huge user base, and those users are uncovering

00:11:01.239 --> 00:11:06.640
bugs which can then be fixed. So really using widely used packages is a great way to sort

00:11:06.640 --> 00:11:12.960
of have free tests in your package. And really the conclusion of all of this is that less

00:11:12.960 --> 00:11:22.039
is not always more when it comes to dependencies. So when you've, I guess, decided that your

00:11:22.039 --> 00:11:26.039
package or project has too many dependencies and you're trying to remove it, how do you

00:11:26.039 --> 00:11:32.359
know what dependencies you want to remove? In this, I think it's really important not

00:11:32.359 --> 00:11:36.760
to just trust your gut in this. I think you need to quantify sort of the weight of each

00:11:36.760 --> 00:11:41.080
dependency in order to figure out which one you should actually remove. And how do you

00:11:41.080 --> 00:11:47.679
do that? So I have this package on GitHub, it depends, that is really aimed to make it

00:11:47.679 --> 00:11:54.799
to be a toolbox for making these types of decisions. So what does this package do? So

00:11:54.799 --> 00:11:59.119
it does a few things. So first, it lets you assess the usage of all the dependencies in

00:11:59.119 --> 00:12:05.479
your package or project. Second, it lets you measure each of those dependencies, measure

00:12:05.479 --> 00:12:10.919
the weights of these dependencies against some of the things that I showed you earlier.

00:12:10.919 --> 00:12:16.760
In addition, it lets you visualize all of your dependencies so you can easily see which

00:12:16.760 --> 00:12:22.559
ones are taking the majority of the time, like installation time or binary size. And

00:12:22.559 --> 00:12:29.440
finally, it has tools to locate and assist removing dependencies. So I'll go through

00:12:29.440 --> 00:12:38.799
all of these in turn. So first, the dep uses proj and dep uses package functions lets you

00:12:38.799 --> 00:12:45.239
determine how you're using dependencies in your project or package. So you basically

00:12:45.239 --> 00:12:53.119
call this and it returns a table of all of the calls for each package, for each dependency

00:12:53.119 --> 00:13:00.520
package in your project. And then I can just count them with dplyr and get a nice count

00:13:00.520 --> 00:13:06.440
of for each package, how many function calls have I used from that package. So we're using

00:13:06.440 --> 00:13:13.719
the base package in this project a bunch. The na row here is functions that I've declared

00:13:13.719 --> 00:13:20.119
inside my project. And then we're using purr and glue a bunch as well. Maybe I want to

00:13:20.119 --> 00:13:26.640
see which functions from those dependency packages I'm using the most. So this is doing

00:13:26.640 --> 00:13:32.919
some other dplyr manipulations to show you that. And this is basically showing the top

00:13:32.919 --> 00:13:42.640
function for each of the dependency packages. So we can do some other. So that was for projects.

00:13:42.640 --> 00:13:46.719
Now we can do the same thing for a package. So this is using dep usage package on the

00:13:46.719 --> 00:13:53.520
DevTools package to count which dependencies I'm using within DevTools. So here we have

00:13:53.520 --> 00:14:03.119
3,000 function calls from the base package, 362 function calls from functions defined

00:14:03.119 --> 00:14:08.760
in the DevTools package itself, and then we're using get to our use this package load. So

00:14:08.760 --> 00:14:15.719
we can easily see which dependencies we're using the most. And so this is very useful

00:14:15.719 --> 00:14:23.359
to see which dependencies maybe we're not using very much and would be easier to remove.

00:14:23.359 --> 00:14:28.679
So once you've sort of whittled down your full list of dependencies and targeted those

00:14:28.679 --> 00:14:33.840
you might want to remove, how do you figure out which ones weigh more or less? We can

00:14:33.840 --> 00:14:40.359
use the depth weight function to do this. So this returns a table of 25 different�

00:14:40.359 --> 00:14:47.679
so it's 25 columns, so 24 different aspects that dependencies can vary on. So here I'm

00:14:47.679 --> 00:14:55.840
weighing two packages, dplyr and datatable, and we're getting a large result of different

00:14:55.840 --> 00:15:00.900
weights. And we'll go through some of these. They don't all fit on one slide, obviously.

00:15:00.900 --> 00:15:06.859
So some examples of things that return. So num user is the number of user dependencies.

00:15:06.859 --> 00:15:11.539
So these are dependencies that a user would install. A num dev is the number of development

00:15:11.539 --> 00:15:17.700
dependencies. So a developer of these packages would install these, but users typically wouldn't.

00:15:17.700 --> 00:15:24.739
The binary self and binary user and binary dev is the binary sizes for the self, the

00:15:24.739 --> 00:15:30.739
user dependencies and the development dependencies. And then the install columns are the mean

00:15:31.700 --> 00:15:37.700
time� or the median time to install each of those packages. And all of the� the user

00:15:37.700 --> 00:15:43.979
and dev is all of the dependency packages. So those are the times to� that CRAN did

00:15:43.979 --> 00:15:51.739
to install those dependencies. So this makes it very easy to tell which packages have more

00:15:51.739 --> 00:16:01.580
dependencies and heavier weight dependencies. Some other things that the depth weight function

00:16:01.580 --> 00:16:06.380
returns is the number of functions in the package. So this gives you an idea of sort

00:16:06.380 --> 00:16:11.140
of the breadth of the package. And also if you contrast the number of functions in the

00:16:11.140 --> 00:16:16.539
package with the number of functions you're using in your package, you get some sense

00:16:16.539 --> 00:16:21.820
of sort of how much of the dependency package you're actually using. If a dependency package

00:16:21.820 --> 00:16:27.700
is very big and you're only using a small subset of that package, maybe you can� it's

00:16:27.700 --> 00:16:33.900
easier to remove that dependency. Other things that this returns is the number

00:16:33.900 --> 00:16:38.380
of weekly downloads. So that's what's in the download column. The time of the first CRAN

00:16:38.380 --> 00:16:43.260
release and the latest CRAN release and the number of releases in the last 52 weeks. So

00:16:43.260 --> 00:16:47.739
these all give you some idea of sort of the age and maturity of the package as well as

00:16:47.739 --> 00:16:53.780
sort of how often it's being updated on CRAN. It also returns some information if the package

00:16:53.780 --> 00:16:58.859
is on GitHub. So this is returning the number of open issues in each package, the number

00:16:58.859 --> 00:17:03.659
of stars, forks, and when it was last updated. So again, this gives you some idea of sort

00:17:03.659 --> 00:17:08.619
of the development speed of the package. And you can see both of these packages are widely

00:17:08.619 --> 00:17:17.260
used and have been updated very frequently. So once you've done this weighting, often

00:17:17.260 --> 00:17:24.699
it's useful to visualize all of the dependencies of your package or project against each other

00:17:24.699 --> 00:17:31.260
and see which dependencies are really taking up the bulk of the time.

00:17:31.260 --> 00:17:38.900
So this plot is showing the dependencies of the dplyr package. And the labels are probably

00:17:38.900 --> 00:17:49.260
too small to read. So the left side, the left facet is, yes, left facet is showing the user

00:17:49.260 --> 00:17:52.579
dependencies. So these are the dependencies that a user would typically install. The right

00:17:52.579 --> 00:17:57.939
one is showing the development dependencies. And if we just focus on the user dependencies,

00:17:57.939 --> 00:18:04.660
you can see this is installation time. So the installing dplyr, building dplyr itself

00:18:04.660 --> 00:18:10.380
is the thing that takes the vast majority of the installation time for dplyr. If we

00:18:10.380 --> 00:18:15.939
change this to looking at the binary size, the picture kind of changes. So now the bh

00:18:15.939 --> 00:18:20.420
package is actually the bulk of the time installing the binary. The binary of that package is

00:18:20.420 --> 00:18:29.859
much bigger than dplyr itself. So now we've sort of targeted, using these tools, we can

00:18:29.859 --> 00:18:34.979
kind of target which dependencies might be the most beneficial to remove. And so once

00:18:34.979 --> 00:18:39.859
we've decided to do this, how do you actually remove a dependency? So first, I think the

00:18:39.859 --> 00:18:43.540
most important thing is to write extensive, like, much, many more tests than you would

00:18:43.540 --> 00:18:49.739
normally write with the dependency in place in your package to make sure you're not introducing

00:18:49.739 --> 00:18:53.939
any new bugs. You will probably introduce new bugs anyway, but really, like, try to

00:18:53.939 --> 00:19:01.579
write tons of tests to avoid this. And then only then will then try to replace the dependency.

00:19:01.579 --> 00:19:08.219
And the it depends package gives you a nice tool to help find all of the uses of the package

00:19:08.219 --> 00:19:16.500
in depth locate. So if you use this, I'm now trying to locate all of the per dependencies

00:19:16.500 --> 00:19:22.819
in this tidyverse dashboard project. And if you run this on the normal R console, you

00:19:22.819 --> 00:19:28.500
get a nice printout of every location of a call to the per package. So this makes it

00:19:28.500 --> 00:19:39.459
very easy to find and remove them. And if you then use this inside the R studio IDE,

00:19:39.459 --> 00:19:43.780
it takes advantage of the marker pane in the IDE, and you get very nice output. And you

00:19:43.780 --> 00:19:47.819
can actually double click on each of these lines in the marker pane, and the IDE will

00:19:47.819 --> 00:19:55.819
take you directly to that line. So it makes it very easy to find and remove a given dependency.

00:19:55.819 --> 00:20:02.859
So in conclusion, this it depends package is really a tool box to let you find all measure

00:20:02.859 --> 00:20:07.739
the usage of your dependency, weigh each of those dependencies, plot them, and then locate

00:20:07.739 --> 00:20:15.420
them. And the sort of big, big point takeaways to this is don't treat dependencies as equivalent.

00:20:15.420 --> 00:20:20.459
You really have to measure and balance and sort of you and weigh the pros and cons of

00:20:20.459 --> 00:20:25.300
having a dependency. Really beware your own overconfidence in your ability to replace

00:20:25.300 --> 00:20:31.099
a dependency. And less in the sort of overall conclusion is less is not always more. So

00:20:31.099 --> 00:20:41.339
thank you, everyone. And the slides are there. So...

00:20:41.339 --> 00:20:46.140
Thank you very much, Jim. Thank you for that introduction. We don't really have time for

